window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>1","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"Which of the following levels of organisation in living things is in the correct sequence, starting from the most complex to me simplest?","images":[],"options":{"A":"tissue \u2192 cell \u2192 organ \u2192 system","B":"System \u2192 organ \u2192 tissue \u2192 cell","C":"Cell \u2192 tissue \u2192 system \u2192 organ","D":"Cell \u2192 tissue \u2192 organ \u2192 system"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct sequence of organization in living things, starting from the most complex to the simplest, is System \u2192 Organ \u2192 Tissue \u2192 Cell. A system is a group of organs that work together to perform a specific function. An organ is a group of tissues that perform a specific function. A tissue is a group of similar cells that work together to perform a specific function. A cell is the basic unit of life.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>2","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"A few drops of fehling's solution was added to juice extracted from fresh maize grain and boiled. A red precipitate was formed, indicating the presence of","images":[],"options":{"A":"alcohol","B":"protein","C":"non-reducing sugar","D":"reducing sugar"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Fehling's solution is specifically used to test for reducing sugars. The formation of a red precipitate upon adding Fehling's solution and boiling indicates the presence of reducing sugars.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>3","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Which of the following is not a cell organelle?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Golgi body","B":"Nucleus","C":"Fat droplets","D":"Ribosome"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Cell organelles are specialized structures within the cell that perform specific functions. The Golgi body, nucleus, and ribosome are all examples of cell organelles. The Golgi body is involved in packaging and transport of proteins, the nucleus houses the cell's DNA and controls the cell's activities, and ribosomes are involved in protein synthesis. Fat droplets, on the other hand, are not considered cell organelles. They are simply accumulations of lipids within the cell, but they do not have a specific function or structure that would classify them as an organelle.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>4","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"One of the differences between plants and animals is that","images":[],"options":{"A":"growth is indefinite in animals but definite in plants","B":"nutrition is autotrophic in plants but holophytic in animals","C":"in plants there are excretory systems but in animals waste products are stored away","D":"plants react slowly to external stimuli while animals react more quickly"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct answer is that plants react slowly to external stimuli while animals react more quickly. This is because plants lack a nervous system and muscles, which in animals allow for quick responses to stimuli. Instead, plants respond to stimuli like light, gravity, and touch through slower processes like differential cell growth and development.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>5","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"Which of the following are the final products of aerobic respiration?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Water, carbondioxide and energy","B":"Pyruvic acid, carbondioxide and water","C":"Glucose, energy and urea","D":"Energy and carbondioxide"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Water: Although water is necessary for many biochemical processes, in the context of aerobic respiration, it is produced as a waste product when oxygen acts as the final electron acceptor in the electron transport chain, combining with hydrogen ions and electrons.  Carbon Dioxide: Carbon dioxide is produced as a waste product during the Krebs cycle when acetyl-CoA is oxidized. Each turn of the Krebs cycle releases two molecules of CO2.  Adenosine Triphosphate (ATP): ATP, the main energy carrier in the cell, is produced through substrate-level phosphorylation in glycolysis and the Krebs cycle, and mainly through oxidative phosphorylation in the electron transport chain. ATP is generated by the addition of a phosphate group to ADP, utilizing the energy released from the transfer of electrons through the electron transport chain.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>6","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"Movement of water across a semi-permeable membrane from a weaker solution to a stronger solution is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"transpiration","B":"diffusion","C":"active transport","D":"osmosis"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The movement of water across a semi-permeable membrane from a weaker solution (lower concentration) to a stronger solution (higher concentration) is known as osmosis. Osmosis is a type of passive transport that occurs naturally, without the need for energy. It's a vital process in biological systems, for example, it regulates the water flow in and out of cells. Transpiration is the process of water movement through a plant and its evaporation from aerial parts, such as leaves, stems and flowers. Diffusion is the movement of molecules from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration. Active transport is the movement of ions or molecules across a cell membrane into a region of higher concentration, assisted by enzymes and requiring energy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>7","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"ln which of the following structures will cells undergoing meiosis be seen?","images":[],"options":{"A":"At the apices of stem and root","B":"In the cortex of the stem","C":"In the pallisade mesophyll of the leaf","D":"ln the ovary of a flower"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Meiosis is a type of cell division that results in four daughter cells each with half the number of chromosomes of the parent cell. It is a process that leads to the formation of sex cells or gametes (sperm and egg cells). In plants, meiosis occurs in the reproductive organs, specifically in the anthers (male) and ovaries (female) of the flower. Therefore, cells undergoing meiosis will be seen in the ovary of a flower.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>8","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of these instruments can be used to perform an experiment on geotropism?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Potometer","B":"Cup anemometer","C":"Klinostat","D":"Kymograph"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A klinostat is a device which uses rotation to negate the effects of gravitational pull on plant growth ( gravitropism) and development ( gravimorphism).   Geotropism is the directional growth of an organism in response to gravity. Roots display positive geotropism when they grow downwards, while shoots display negative geotropism when they grow upwards. A Klinostat is an instrument used to negate the effect of gravity and light on the growth of plants, thus it can be used to perform an experiment on geotropism. A Potometer is used to measure the rate of transpiration in plants, a Cup anemometer is used to measure wind speed, and a Kymograph is used to record variations in pressure, velocity and other variables.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>9","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The thoracic vertebra differs from all the other vertebrae by the possession of","images":[],"options":{"A":"long neural spine","B":"odontoid process","C":"vertebraterial canal","D":"Large centrum"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The thoracic vertebrae are most distinctly characterized by their long neural spines. This feature is specific and easily identifiable compared to other vertebrae.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>10","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Study the list below  The vertebral column of mammals consists of the following:  I. Lumbar vertebrae II. Thoracic vertebrae III. Caudal vertebrae IV Cervical vertebrae V. Sacral vertebrae.    Which of the following are found immediately next to the skull?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The vertebral column of mammals is divided into several regions, which from top to bottom are: the cervical, thoracic, lumbar, sacral, and caudal vertebrae. The cervical vertebrae are the ones found immediately next to the skull. Therefore, the correct answer is IV. Cervical vertebrae.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>11","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Study the list below  The vertebral column of mammals consists of the following:  I. Lumbar vertebrae II. Thoracic vertebrae III. Caudal vertebrae IV Cervical vertebrae V. Sacral vertebrae. Which of the following articulates with the ribs?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The thoracic vertebrae articulate with the ribs. The thoracic vertebrae are the only vertebrae that have facets on their bodies and transverse processes for rib articulation. The ribs connect to the thoracic vertebrae at two points: the head of the rib connects to the body of the vertebrae and the tubercle of the rib connects to the transverse process. This allows for the movement of the ribs during respiration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>12","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Study the list below  The vertebral column of mammals consists of the following:  I. Lumbar vertebrae II. Thoracic vertebrae III. Caudal vertebrae IV Cervical vertebrae V. Sacral vertebrae. Which of the following articulates with the pelvic girdle?","images":[],"options":{"A":"V","B":"IV","C":"III","D":"II"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The vertebral column of mammals consists of several types of vertebrae. The sacral vertebrae (option V) are the ones that articulate with the pelvic girdle. The sacrum is a large, triangular bone at the base of the spine and at the upper and back part of the pelvic cavity, where it is inserted like a wedge between the two hip bones. Its upper part connects with the last lumbar vertebra, and bottom part with the coccyx (tailbone).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>13","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following is more concentrated in the blood within the renal artery than the blood within the renal vein?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Urea","B":"Red blood cells","C":"Glucose","D":"Protein"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The renal artery carries blood to the kidneys for filtration. During this process, waste products such as urea are removed from the blood. Therefore, the concentration of urea is higher in the blood within the renal artery than in the blood within the renal vein, which carries filtered blood away from the kidneys. The other options (red blood cells, glucose, protein) are not typically removed or significantly reduced during filtration, so their concentrations would not be higher in the renal artery than in the renal vein.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>14","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"Which of the following statements about the lymphatic system is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The lymph vessels are always larger in size than the arteries","B":"The flow of lymph is assisted by general muscular movement","C":"Lymph flows only in one direction due to the presence of valves","D":"Lymph is emptied into the blood circulatory system through a vein"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The lymphatic system is a network of tissues and organs that help rid the body of toxins, waste and other unwanted materials. The primary function of the lymphatic system is to transport lymph, a fluid containing infection-fighting white blood cells, throughout the body. The lymph vessels are not always larger in size than the arteries. In fact, they are generally smaller. The other options are correct: the flow of lymph is indeed assisted by general muscular movement, lymph does flow only in one direction due to the presence of valves, and lymph is emptied into the blood circulatory system through a vein.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>15","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"In which of the following groups is nephridium found?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Crustaceans","B":"Reptiles","C":"Birds","D":"Annelids"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Annelida, also called segmented worm, any member of a phylum of invertebrate animals that are characterized by the possession of a body cavity (or coelom ), movable bristles (or setae ), and a body divided into segments by transverse rings. a segmented worm of the phylum Annelida, such as an earthworm or leech.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>16","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REGULATION OF INTERNAL ENVIRONMENT (HOMEOSTASIS)","question":"The maintenance of a constant internal environment of an organism is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"homeostasis","B":"homeorhesis","C":"turgidity","D":"homoiothermy"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The maintenance of a constant internal environment of an organism is known as homeostasis. Homeostasis is a biological concept referring to the ability of an organism or cell to maintain equilibrium by adjusting its physiological processes. The other options do not correctly define this concept. Homeorhesis refers to the stability of a pathway, process or system. Turgidity is the state of being swollen or distended, often in relation to plant cells. Homoiothermy is the ability of some organisms to maintain a stable body temperature.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>17","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT","question":"Which of the following is the effect of continuous tillage on an ecological system?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Addition of more. humus to the soil","B":"Decrease in productivity","C":"Increase in yield","D":"Improved fertility"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Continuous tillage of an ecological system often leads to a decrease in productivity. This is because continuous tillage can lead to soil degradation, which in turn reduces the soil's ability to support plant growth. Soil degradation can occur as a result of various factors, including erosion, compaction, nutrient imbalance, and disruption of soil organisms. None of the other options are correct because continuous tillage does not add more humus to the soil, does not increase yield, and does not improve fertility. In fact, it often has the opposite effect.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>18","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"The most sensitive part of the retina is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"blindspot","B":"conjuctiva","C":"fovea centralis","D":"choroid coat"},"answer":"C","explanation":"fovea centralis; a small depression in the retina of the eye where visual acuity is highest. The centre of the field of vision is focused in this region, where retinal cones are particularly concentrated.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>19","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Which of the following pairs consists of gametes?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Ova and spermatozoa","B":"Spores and sporangium","C":"Flowers and pollen grains","D":"Testes and ovaries"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Gametes are the reproductive cells that combine to form offspring. In humans and many other species, there are two main types of gametes, and these are sperm (from males) and eggs or ova (from females). Therefore, the pair that consists of gametes is 'Ova and spermatozoa'. Spores and sporangium, Flowers and pollen grains, Testes and ovaries are not pairs of gametes. Spores are reproductive cells in fungi, algae, and plants, but sporangium is a structure that produces and contains spores, not a gamete. Flowers and pollen grains are parts of plants, but only pollen grains can be considered as gametes (male gametes in plants). Testes and ovaries are reproductive organs that produce gametes, but they are not gametes themselves.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>20","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Which of the labelled structures is the nucleus?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The nucleus of the sperm cell, which houses the DNA, is located within the head. Label II points to this specific region.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>21","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"Which of the following labelled structures secretes enzymes which facilitate penetration of the egg?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Structure I (labelled in the image) is located at the head of the sperm cell. The acrosome is situated at the anterior part of the sperm head and contains hydrolytic enzymes. These enzymes are released upon contact with the egg's zona pellucida to facilitate sperm penetration through this protective layer during fertilization.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>22","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"Which of the following labelled structures is similar to the locomotory structure in Euglena?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"V"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Among the labelled options (I, II, III, IV, V), the correct answer is (V). Structure V (labelled in the image) corresponds to a flagellum. Flagella are long, whip-like appendages used for locomotion in many organisms, including Euglena. Euglena uses its flagellum to move through water by beating it in a characteristic waving motion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>23","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"The part labelled I in A represents the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"root","B":"radicle","C":"hypocotyl","D":"shoot"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The part labelled I in A represents the hypocotyl. The hypocotyl is the first part of the embryo to emerge from a seed that has been planted in the soil.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>24","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"The part labelled II represents the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"root","B":"epicotyl","C":"hypocotyl","D":"cotyledon"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Cotyledons are seed leaves that serve essential functions during the early stages of a plant's life, particularly before it can photosynthesize on its own.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>25","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"What is the importance of the part labelled II to the seedling? It","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"protects the foliage leaves","B":"grows into the first foliage leaves","C":"later develops into the fruit","D":"provides the seedling with food"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Cotyledons play a vital role in the early development and survival of seedlings by providing nutrients, protection, and sometimes even contributing to photosynthesis until the plant becomes self-sufficient with its true leaves.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>26","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"In grasshopper/cockroach digestion starts from the","images":[],"options":{"A":"oesophagus","B":"crop","C":"gizzard","D":"mouth"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In grasshoppers and cockroaches, digestion starts from the mouth. The food is first ingested through the mouth where it is broken down into smaller pieces by the mandibles (jaws). The food is then mixed with saliva for further breakdown. Therefore, the correct answer is 'mouth'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>27","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"In a water culture experiment, the culture solution in a transparent beaker turned green. What precaution should have been taken to prevent the culture solution from turning green?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Changing the culture solution regularly","B":"Increasing the number of times the culture is aerated","C":"Covering the transparent beaker with black cloth","D":"Adding warm alcohol to bleach the green colour"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The culture solution turned green because of the growth of algae, which is facilitated by light. Covering the transparent beaker with a black cloth would prevent light from reaching the solution, thereby inhibiting the growth of algae. Changing the culture solution regularly or increasing the number of times the culture is aerated would not necessarily prevent the growth of algae. Adding warm alcohol would not prevent the growth of algae, but rather kill them and possibly other organisms in the culture solution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>28","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : NITROGEN CYCLE","question":"Which of the following is responsible for the conversion of nitrites to nitrates in the nitrogen cycle?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Denitrifying bacteria","B":"Nitrifying bacteria","C":"Lightening","D":"Fungi"},"answer":"B","explanation":"As nitrifying bacteria name signifies the conversion of ammonia into nitrites or nitrates. These are the bacterias that break down the nitrated and return nitrogen to the air. Nitrification is the biological oxidation of ammonia to nitrite followed by the oxidation of the nitrite to nitrate occurring through separate organisms","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>29","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Hydra captures small crustaceans by means of","images":[],"options":{"A":"pseudopodia","B":"musculo-epithelial cells","C":"tentacles","D":"enteron"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Hydra, a small, simple aquatic animal, captures its prey, which includes small crustaceans, by means of its tentacles. The tentacles are equipped with specialized cells called cnidocytes, which contain structures called nematocysts. When a prey animal comes into contact with the tentacles, the nematocysts are triggered, firing a barbed thread that penetrates and immobilizes the prey. The prey is then moved to the mouth opening by the tentacles. Therefore, the correct answer is 'tentacles'. Pseudopodia are extensions of the cell used by some protozoans for movement or capturing food, which is not applicable to Hydra. Musculo-epithelial cells are a type of cell found in Hydra, but they are not directly involved in capturing prey. The enteron is the digestive cavity of the Hydra, not the means by which it captures prey.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>30","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"Which of the following processes is not due to interaction between the biotic and abiotic components of an ecosystem?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Soil nutrient depletion","B":"Condensation","C":"Decomposition","D":"Osmosis"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The interaction between biotic (living organisms) and abiotic (non-living elements) components of an ecosystem results in processes like soil nutrient depletion, decomposition, and osmosis. Soil nutrient depletion occurs when plants absorb nutrients from the soil, which is an interaction between a biotic component (plants) and an abiotic component (soil). Decomposition is the process by which dead organic substances are broken down into simpler organic or inorganic matter such as carbon dioxide, water, simple sugars and mineral salts, which is an interaction between biotic components (decomposers like bacteria and fungi) and abiotic components (dead organic matter). Osmosis is the process by which water molecules move from a region of lower concentration to a region of higher concentration through a semi-permeable membrane, which is an interaction between biotic components (cells) and abiotic components (water). However, condensation is a physical process where water vapor becomes liquid. It is a part of the water cycle, and it happens when the temperature drops or the amount of moisture in the air increases. It is not due to interaction between the biotic and abiotic components of an ecosystem.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>31","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"The entire habits and habitat of an organism can be described as its","images":[],"options":{"A":"ecological community","B":"ecological niche","C":"habitat factor","D":"biotic factor"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The entire habits and habitat of an organism can be described as its ecological niche.   In biology and ecology, a niche pertains to any of the following:    The specific area where an organism inhabits  The role or function of an organism or species in an ecosystem  The interrelationship of a species with all the biotic and abiotic factors affecting it","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>32","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Which of these is not a true characteristic of the tropical rain forest?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Vegetation consists predominantly of tall trees, with thick canopy","B":"Forest is rich in epipphysis and climbers","C":"Annual rainfall is less than 100 cm","D":"interior has low light intensity, high humidity and damp floor"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tropical rainforests are characterized by high rainfall, with minimum normal annual rainfall between 1750\u20132000 mm (68-78 inches). Therefore, the statement 'Annual rainfall is less than 100 cm' is not a true characteristic of the tropical rain forest.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>33","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"The frequency of andropogon in a grass lawn is 90 by 100. Throws were made with 1 meter square quadrat. What is the density of andropogon in the field?","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.09 per m2","B":"0.90 per m2","C":"9.0 per m2","D":"90 per m2"},"answer":"B","explanation":"If a 1-meter square quadrat is used, the population density will be 90/100 per m2. So, the answer is 0.90 peer m2","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>34","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following is the correct method of collecting soil organism?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Heating the soil sample in an oven","B":"Aerating the soil sample","C":"Refrigerating the soil for some hours","D":"Placing a lighted electric bulb over soil in a funnel"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct method of collecting soil organisms is by placing a lighted electric bulb over soil in a funnel. This method is known as the Tullgren funnel method. The heat from the bulb dries the soil, causing the organisms to move downwards and eventually fall into a collecting jar placed beneath the funnel.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>35","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"Which of these groups of organisms is responsible for capturing energy for the biotic community?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Decomposers","B":"Omnivores","C":"Consumers","D":"Producers"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Producers is responsible for capturing energy for the biotic community. At the base of almost every food chain is a producer. These are plants or algae, which photosynthesise. This means they convert energy from the sun into glucose during photosynthesis, which produces biomass. It is this which feeds the rest of the food chain.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>36","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"The following are pathways of energy in the biosphere  I. Heat energy is lost from body metabolism to the surrounding air   II. Energy passes to decomposers and parasites   III. Energy is transferred to the next higher level in a food chain   IV. Energy is also passed by conduction to clothing and other objects    Which pathway directly leads to transfer of useful energy within a biological community?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I only","B":"II and III only","C":"I and III only","D":"I and II only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a biological community, energy is transferred in various ways. The useful energy transfer within a biological community is through the food chain and to decomposers and parasites. In a food chain, energy is transferred from one trophic level to the next higher level. This is represented by statement III. Decomposers and parasites also play a crucial role in energy transfer as they break down dead organisms and waste materials, releasing the energy stored in them back into the ecosystem. This is represented by statement II. Therefore, the correct answer is 'II and III only'. Heat energy lost from body metabolism to the surrounding air (statement I) and energy passed by conduction to clothing and other objects (statement IV) are forms of energy loss, not useful energy transfer within a biological community.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>37","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"The following are pathways of energy in the biosphere  I. Heat energy is lost from body metabolism to the surrounding air   II. Energy passes to decomposers and parasites   III. Energy is transferred to the next higher level in a food chain   IV. Energy is also passed by conduction to clothing and other objects   Which of the following pathways will energy follow to reach plasmodium in the red blood cells?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I, II and III","B":"I and II","C":"II only","D":"III and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Plasmodium is a parasite that lives in the red blood cells of its host. Therefore, the energy pathway to reach plasmodium in the red blood cells is through decomposers and parasites (II). The other pathways (I, III, IV) are not relevant to the energy flow to plasmodium.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>38","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATIONS","question":"What type of relationship exists in the large intestine of the sheep, between bacteria and the sheep?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Symbiosis","B":"Commensalism","C":"Predation","D":"Parasitism"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A symbiosis is an evolved interaction or close living relationship between organisms from different species, usually with benefits to one or both of the individuals involved.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>39","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The Tulgren's funnel is used to","images":[],"options":{"A":"extract minute soil organisms","B":"measure the amount of rainfall","C":"collect water from habitats","D":"pour liquid into containers with narrow mouth"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Tullgren's funnel is a device used in soil biology to extract small soil-dwelling animals, including insects, mites, spiders, and other minute soil organisms. The device works by applying a heat source from above which drives the organisms downwards and they eventually fall into a collecting jar. Therefore, the correct answer is 'extract minute soil organisms'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>40","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Which of the following is not an aquatic habitat?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Estuaries","B":"Ponds","C":"Rainforest","D":"Swamp"},"answer":"C","explanation":"An aquatic habitat is a habitat with water. It includes areas that are permanently covered by water and surrounding areas that are occasionally covered by water. Estuaries, ponds, and swamps are all types of aquatic habitats as they contain water. However, a rainforest is not an aquatic habitat. It is a terrestrial habitat characterized by high rainfall, with annual rainfall in the case of tropical rainforests between 2.5 and 4.5 meters, and definitions varying by region for temperate rainforests.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>41","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"Which of these materials is not required for insect collection in an ecological field-trip?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Pooter","B":"Secchi disc","C":"Spreading board","D":"Jar containing alcohol"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A Secchi disc is not required for insect collection in an ecological field-trip. A Secchi disc is a circular disc used to measure water transparency in oceans and lakes. The other options, Pooter, Spreading board, and Jar containing alcohol, are all tools commonly used in insect collection. A Pooter is a device used for catching small insects and other small creatures. A Spreading board is used to pin and display collected insects, and a Jar containing alcohol is used to preserve collected insects.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>42","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The factors which determine the type of vegetation a particular habitat will support are related to the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"nature of the soil particles","B":"amount of rainfall","C":"mineral content of the soil","D":"farming activities"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The factors which determine the type of vegetation a particular habitat will support are related to several factors, including the nature of the soil particles, the amount of rainfall, the mineral content of the soil, and the depth of the water-table. However, farming activities are not a natural factor but a human activity that can alter the natural vegetation and ecosystem of an area.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>43","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"Which of the following statements is not true of population?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Members of a population may be of the same species","B":"Members of a population may be of the same species but do not interbreed","C":"Size of a population may be limited by space","D":"Some species can form another population elsewhere"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A population is a group of individuals of the same species that live in the same area and interbreed. Therefore, the statement 'Members of a population may be of the same species but do not interbreed' is not true of a population. All other options correctly describe characteristics of a population.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>44","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following is an abiotic factor which affects a population?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Predator","B":"Parasite","C":"Consumer","D":"Temperature"},"answer":"D","explanation":"An abiotic factor refers to non-living physical and chemical elements in the ecosystem. Abiotic factors could include temperature, light, water, air, soil, pH, and nutrients. These factors have a significant impact on the survival and reproduction of species in an ecosystem. In the given options, 'Temperature' is an abiotic factor. Predators, parasites, and consumers are all biotic factors, meaning they are living organisms that affect a population.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>45","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"One of the ecological conditions which favour the spread of malaria is","images":[],"options":{"A":"improper disposal of decaying organic matter","B":"clearing bushes around dwelling houses","C":"presence of water weeds","D":"presence of stagnant water in ponds"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Malaria is a disease caused by a parasite that is transmitted to humans through the bite of the female Anopheles mosquito. These mosquitoes breed in areas with stagnant water. Therefore, the presence of stagnant water in ponds creates a favorable environment for the breeding of these mosquitoes, leading to the spread of malaria. The other options do not directly relate to the spread of malaria.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>46","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"Which of the following resources is non-renewable?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Livestock","B":"Minerals","C":"Forest","D":"Soil"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A non-renewable resource is a resource that does not renew itself at a sufficient rate for sustainable economic extraction in meaningful human timeframes. Minerals are considered non-renewable resources as they do not form or replenish in a short period of time. Livestock, forests, and soil are all renewable resources because they can be replenished naturally in a relatively short amount of time.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>47","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT","question":"The following are the effects of overgrazing except","images":[],"options":{"A":"depletion of useful fodder crops","B":"soil and wind erosion of pastureland","C":"epidemic of cattle diseases","D":"migration of herdsmen"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Overgrazing refers to the situation where plants are exposed to intensive grazing for extended periods of time, or without sufficient recovery periods. It can be caused by either livestock in poorly managed agricultural applications, or by overpopulations of native or non-native wild animals. Overgrazing reduces the usefulness, productivity, and biodiversity of the land and is one cause of desertification and erosion. It's effects include depletion of useful fodder crops and soil and wind erosion of pastureland. However, it does not directly cause an epidemic of cattle diseases. Diseases in cattle can be caused by a variety of factors including bacteria, viruses, parasites, and certain environmental factors, but not directly by overgrazing. Therefore, the statement 'epidemic of cattle diseases' is not an effect of overgrazing.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>48","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"Which of the following is not a way of conserving natural resources?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Adopting good farming practices","B":"Establishing forest reserves","C":"Establishing of game reserves","D":"Encouraging poaching"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Conservation of natural resources involves practices that protect, preserve, and sustainably manage these resources. Good farming practices help to maintain soil fertility and prevent soil erosion. Establishing forest reserves and game reserves helps to protect biodiversity by providing habitats for various species. However, poaching, which is the illegal hunting or capturing of wild animals, is not a way of conserving natural resources. Instead, it threatens biodiversity and can lead to the extinction of species.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>49","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"The need for conservation includes the following except to","images":[],"options":{"A":"keep natural resources for future generations","B":"preserve them for scientific and recreational purposes","C":"maximise the use of natural resources","D":"make sure the natural resources are not used"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Conservation is the sustainable use and management of natural resources including wildlife, water, air, and earth deposits. The aim of conservation is not to make sure the natural resources are not used, but rather to ensure that they are used in a sustainable manner that ensures their availability for future generations, for scientific and recreational purposes, and to maximize their use. Therefore, the option 'make sure the natural resources are not used' is not a reason for conservation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>50","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of these is not a hereditary variation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Infant paralysis","B":"Blood group","C":"Sickle cell","D":"Shape of face and nose"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Hereditary variations are differences that are passed from parents to offspring through genes. These include traits like blood group, sickle cell trait, and physical features like the shape of face and nose. Infant paralysis, however, is not a hereditary variation. It is a condition that can occur due to various reasons such as injury, illness, or malnutrition, but it is not passed down through genes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>51","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of these statements is correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Recombination at fertilization does not occur between two homologous chromosome","B":"In homologous chromosome two genes very close to each other are more likely to form recombinants meiotic prophase I","C":"A dominant gene masks the presence of a recessive gene","D":"Meiosis leads to the formation of daughter cells with diploid chromosome number"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A dominant gene masks the presence of a recessive gene. This is a fundamental principle of genetics. In a pair of alleles, if one is dominant and the other is recessive, the dominant allele will express itself in the phenotype, effectively 'masking' the presence of the recessive allele. This is why the recessive trait only appears when an individual has two copies of the recessive allele. The other options are incorrect. Recombination does occur between homologous chromosomes during meiosis, genes close to each other on a chromosome are less likely to recombine due to genetic linkage, and meiosis results in haploid, not diploid, daughter cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>52","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY","question":"One of Mendel's experiments was repeated by crossing a red variety of pepper with that of a yellow variety which produced all red offspring. The red offspring were then self pollinated and these produced both red and yellow pepper. The yellow colour can be said to be","images":[],"options":{"A":"dominant to red","B":"recessive to red","C":"homozygous to red","D":"heterozygous to red"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In Mendelian genetics, a trait that appears in the first generation (F1) when parents with different traits are crossed is said to be dominant, while the trait that is masked in the F1 generation but reappears in the second generation (F2) is said to be recessive. In the given question, the red color appears in the F1 generation when a red pepper is crossed with a yellow pepper, indicating that red is the dominant trait. The yellow color, which is masked in the F1 generation but reappears in the F2 generation, is therefore the recessive trait. Hence, the yellow color is recessive to red.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>53","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"Which of the following statements is not true about chromosomes?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Each chromosome is made up of two chromatids","B":"Body cells have diploid numbers of chromosomes","C":"Homologous chromosomes do not occur in pairs naturally","D":"The sex cells have haploid number of chromosomes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Homologous chromosomes do not occur in pairs naturally is not true about chromosomes. Homologous chromosomes occur in pairs naturally in diploid organisms. Homologous chromosomes are similar in size, shape, and carry genes for the same traits, but they may have different versions of those genes. During meiosis, homologous chromosomes pair up and exchange genetic information through a process called crossing over, which contributes to genetic diversity","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>54","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY","question":"Cross-breeding is a way of","images":[],"options":{"A":"developing superior varieties of plants only","B":"developing superior varieties of animals only","C":"developing disease-resistant varieties only","D":"applying the principles of heredity in agriculture"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Cross-breeding is a method used in agriculture to combine the desirable traits of two different species or varieties to produce a superior variety. This method is not limited to plants or animals only, it can be applied to both. It is also not limited to developing disease-resistant varieties only, it can be used to improve various traits such as yield, quality, adaptability to environmental conditions, etc. Therefore, the correct answer is 'applying the principles of heredity in agriculture'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>55","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"The wings of bats and birds, the flippers of whale and the fins of fish are examples of","images":[],"options":{"A":"adaptive radiation","B":"vestigial organs","C":"continuous variation","D":"convergent evolution"},"answer":"D","explanation":". The wings of bats, birds, the flippers of whales, and the fins of fish are all examples of structures that have evolved independently in different groups of animals, but serve similar functions. This is known as convergent evolution, where unrelated organisms evolve similar structures or functions due to similar selection pressures. In this case, the ability to fly, swim, or move through the water efficiently, respectively, has led to the development of these similar structures","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>56","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Which of the following is a social insect?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Mosquito","B":"Butterfly","C":"Honey bee","D":"Grasshopper"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Honey bee is a social insect.social insect, any of numerous species of insects that live in colonies and manifest three characteristics: group integration, division of labour, and overlap of generations. Social insects are best exemplified by all termites (Isoptera; sometimes Blattodea) and ants.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>57","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"The phenomenon whereby some organisms get established in an environment after struggling for existence by taking advantage of some special features possessed by the organism is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"partial selection","B":"artificial selection","C":"natural selection","D":"mutation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The phenomenon described in the question is known as natural selection. Natural selection is a process where organisms that are better adapted to their environment tend to survive and produce more offspring. This process makes them get established in an environment after struggling for existence by taking advantage of some special features possessed by the organism. The other options do not accurately describe this process. Partial selection and artificial selection are not natural processes, and mutation is a change in the DNA sequence, not a process of survival and establishment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>58","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"The statements below are about evolution of species  I. Members of a species vary ll. Organisms produce many offspring lll. The mechanism of evolution is  inheritance of acquired characters IV. Changes in the phenotype is brought about by the individual itself    Which of the statement(s) is/are related to the Darwin's theory of evolution?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I only","B":"II only","C":"I, II and IV","D":"I and II only"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Darwin's theory of evolution, also known as Darwinism, includes two key ideas: that evolution occurs and that evolution occurs through natural selection. Statement I, 'Members of a species vary', refers to the concept of variation, which is a fundamental aspect of Darwin's theory. Statement II, 'Organisms produce many offspring', refers to the concept of overproduction, which is also a key aspect of Darwin's theory. Overproduction leads to competition for resources, and those individuals with advantageous variations are more likely to survive and reproduce. Therefore, statements I and II are related to Darwin's theory of evolution. Statements III and IV are not related to Darwin's theory. Statement III, 'The mechanism of evolution is inheritance of acquired characters', refers to Lamarck's theory of evolution, not Darwin's. Statement IV, 'Changes in the phenotype is brought about by the individual itself', is also not part of Darwin's theory. Therefore, the correct answer is 'I and II only'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>59","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following fields of study may not yield strong evidence of evolution?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Fossil","B":"Histology","C":"Ecology","D":"Genetics"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Evolution is the process of change in all forms of life over generations. It is studied through various fields such as genetics, paleontology (study of fossils), comparative anatomy, and molecular biology. Among the given options, 'Ecology' is the least likely to yield strong evidence of evolution. Ecology is the study of the interactions between organisms and their environment. While it can provide some insights into the adaptive strategies of organisms, it does not directly deal with the genetic changes over generations that is the core of evolutionary studies. Therefore, the answer is 'Ecology'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1996>60","subject":"Biology","year":"1996","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following is the simplest method of finding the magnification of the drawing of a specimen?","images":[],"options":{"A":"(length of drawing/width of drawing) / (length of specimen/width of specimen)","B":"(length of specimen/width of specimen) / (length of drawing/width of drawing)","C":"length of drawing x 2/ length of specimen","D":"length of drawing / width of specimen"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Magnification=(length of drawing/width of drawing) / (length of specimen/width of specimen)","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"}];